\section{Introduction}
% -------------------------------------------------------

Traditional educational assessments adopt a one-size-fits-all model, presenting identical questions to all students regardless of individual competency. This approach inherently assumes uniform learning ability and pace among learners, which is rarely the case in real-world educational environments. As a result, high-performing students may find the assessment too easy and unchallenging, while low-performing students may struggle excessively, leading to frustration and disengagement. Consequently, such systems fail to capture the true ability of learners at either extreme of the performance spectrum and provide little actionable insight for instructors regarding individual strengths, weaknesses, and learning trajectories \cite{weiss2004}.

Furthermore, most existing assessment systems provide limited or generic feedback that does not help students understand their specific areas of strength and weakness. This lack of personalization hinders accurate competency measurement, reduces student engagement, and limits learning efficiency \cite{vygotsky1978}. Without continuous adaptation based on student performance, assessments remain rigid and unable to reflect the dynamic nature of learning \cite{mislevy2003}.

Computerized Adaptive Testing (CAT) addresses these limitations by adjusting question difficulty based on ongoing responses \cite{lord1980}. However, most CAT systems rely on Item Response Theory (IRT), requiring large-scale pre-calibrated item banks and statistically validated parameters \cite{hambleton1985}. This limits applicability in smaller settings and makes question selection difficult to interpret for educators.

Recent advances in Large Language Models (LLMs) offer an alternative: encoding adaptation logic directly into intelligent agents. LLM-powered agents can reason over correctness and response time holistically, applying natural language adaptation rules for context-aware difficulty decisions.

Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024} proposed the APOT (Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit) model managed by a Multi-Agent System (MAS) for competency building, introducing the Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA), Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SOLMA), Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SOLPA), and Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SOLTA). While their framework provides a strong foundation, it targets augmented reality (AR)-based vocational training and relies on deterministic KPI metrics. Our system adapts the APOT model's cyclic stages and agent role separation into a fully LLM-driven, question-based adaptive testing environment.

This paper proposes an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System with the following contributions:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item A three-agent CrewAI pipeline powered by Gemini 2.5 Flash mapping to the APOT agents (SOLMA, SOLPA, SOLTA), replacing formula-driven scoring with LLM-native contextual reasoning.
    \item A dual-layer difficulty adaptation combining synchronous rule-based fallback with asynchronous multi-agent LLM analysis, and LLM-driven dynamic question generation eliminating static item bank dependence.
    \item An interpretable, prompt-engineered adaptation mechanism that eliminates IRT pre-calibration while maintaining responsiveness and explainability across three cognitive domains.
\end{enumerate}

% -------------------------------------------------------
\section{Related Work}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Multi-Agent Systems in Education}
Multi-Agent Systems (MAS) have gained significant attention in educational technology \cite{wooldridge2009}. Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024} proposed the APOT model with four agents: the \textbf{LSAA} (Learning Style Assessment Agent), evaluating learner modality preferences; the \textbf{SOLMA} (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent), monitoring current performance; the \textbf{SOLPA} (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent), predicting learner potential; and the \textbf{SOLTA} (Stage of Learning Transition Agent), determining competency stage transitions. These agents compute a Learning Index (LI) and Competency Index (CI) to track progress. However, their framework targets vocational AR training, limiting applicability to digital question-based assessment \cite{outay2024}. Our work adapts the APOT philosophy to a question-driven setting, replacing quantitative KPIs with LLM-based reasoning.

\subsection{Computerized Adaptive Testing}
CAT has been studied extensively since the 1970s and is widely regarded as a robust method for personalized assessment \cite{weiss2004}. CAT systems typically rely on IRT, where each question is associated with parameters such as difficulty, discrimination, and guessing probability \cite{lord1980}. While statistically rigorous, IRT-based CAT systems require large, well-calibrated item banks that are expensive and time-consuming to develop \cite{hambleton1985}. The probabilistic nature of IRT models also makes them difficult to interpret for educators. Our approach replaces IRT with LLM-based agents that reason over observable performance signals---correctness and time---using transparent natural language rules, offering ease of deployment without sacrificing adaptive responsiveness.

\subsection{LLM-Augmented Assessment Frameworks}
Recent LLM advances have enabled integration into educational systems for feedback, tutoring, and content creation \cite{chen2023}. Frameworks such as CrewAI \cite{liang2023} and AutoGen facilitate LLM-augmented agent collaboration. Bloom's taxonomy \cite{bloom1956} informs our three-level difficulty scheme (Easy, Medium, Hard). Reinforcement learning \cite{sutton2018} and Bayesian student models \cite{conati2002} offer alternatives but require extensive training data. Unlike prior systems restricting LLMs to feedback only, our system delegates the full assessment pipeline---evaluation, difficulty prediction, and adaptation---to LLM agents.

