\section{Multi-Agent Framework}
% -------------------------------------------------------

All agents are powered by Gemini 2.5 Flash via CrewAI's LLM interface (temperature 0.7), executing sequentially with context passing between tasks.

\subsection{MCQ Evaluator Agent (SOLMA)}
The MCQ Evaluator implements \textbf{SOLMA} (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent), the APOT \textit{Assess} phase. Just as the original SOLMA monitors a learner's current performance \cite{outay2024}, our agent monitors the student's immediate response quality. Its role is strictly defined as a fair and accurate MCQ examiner: given the question, correct answer, student's answer, and time taken, it determines correctness and provides a one-line explanation. Configured with \texttt{allow\_delegation=False}, it isolates factual judgment from difficulty reasoning.

The agent's task receives a structured input block containing:
\begin{itemize}
    \item The question text
    \item The correct answer
    \item The student's selected answer
    \item The time taken in seconds
\end{itemize}
Its expected output is a binary correctness verdict with a brief justification, providing the factual foundation for subsequent agents.

\subsection{Difficulty Predictor Agent (SOLPA)}
The Difficulty Predictor implements \textbf{SOLPA} (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent), the APOT \textit{Predict} phase. It classifies the current question as Easy, Medium, or Hard based on SOLMA's verdict and response time. The backstory encodes: ``Fast + Correct = Easy. Slow + Correct = Medium. Wrong = Hard.'' This mirrors the insight that response time with correctness serves as a behavioral proxy for difficulty \cite{weiss2004}. No hard-coded thresholds are imposed; the LLM interprets ``fast''/``slow'' contextually.

\subsection{Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent (SOLTA)}
The Adaptive Overseer implements \textbf{SOLTA} (Stage of Learning Transition Agent), serving both \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} phases. Where the original SOLTA determines when and how a learner should transition between competency stages \cite{outay2024}, our agent determines when and how to transition between difficulty levels. It receives SOLMA and SOLPA outputs as context, producing: (1) confirmed current difficulty, and (2) recommended next difficulty. Its backstory encodes adaptive rules grounded in the Zone of Proximal Development \cite{vygotsky1978} and Bloom's taxonomy \cite{bloom1956}:

\textbf{If the answer is correct:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Easy $\rightarrow$ Next: Medium (increase challenge)
    \item Medium $\rightarrow$ Next: Hard (advance to next level)
    \item Hard $\rightarrow$ Next: Hard or Medium (maintain mastery)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{If the answer is incorrect:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Hard $\rightarrow$ Next: Medium (step down one level)
    \item Medium $\rightarrow$ Next: Easy (step down one level)
    \item Easy $\rightarrow$ Next: Easy (stay at same level for confidence building)
\end{itemize}

Configured with \texttt{allow\_delegation=True}, the agent can consult prior agents if additional clarification is needed. Its output follows a structured natural language format parsed line-by-line via keyword matching, with ``Medium'' defaults on failure:

\begin{verbatim}
Questions Difficulty: [Easy/Medium/Hard]
Next Question Difficulty: [Easy/Medium/Hard]
Reasoning: [explanation]
Recommendation: [additional actions]
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{LSAA Function}
The \textbf{LSAA} (Learning Style Assessment Agent) function is distributed across domain-aware question generation tailoring MCQs to Reasoning, Aptitude, or Verbal Ability, and multi-domain competency tracking identifying the weakest domain for targeted feedback.

\subsection{CrewAI Orchestration}
The three agents are assembled into a \texttt{Crew} with \texttt{Process.sequential}, \texttt{memory=False}, and \texttt{max\_rpm=10}. Task 3 (SOLTA) declares \texttt{context=[task1, task2]} for access to SOLMA and SOLPA outputs. \texttt{crew.kickoff()} executes the pipeline and returns SOLTA's output. Fig.~\ref{fig:pipeline} illustrates the pipeline.

