\subsection{Competency Analytics and Data Models}
Beyond per-question adaptation, the system provides longitudinal competency tracking. The dashboard computes a Competency Index (CI) as a weighted average over the ten most recent completed tests with harmonic weights (weight = 1/rank), ensuring recent performance has greater influence over historical averages. Per-domain accuracy (Aptitude, Reasoning, Verbal) is tracked independently, and the weakest domain is identified for targeted feedback. Competency bands are assigned on the leaderboard: Expert ($\geq$85), Advanced ($\geq$70), Intermediate ($\geq$50), and Beginner ($<$50).

The persistence layer comprises three interconnected models providing a complete audit trail. \texttt{StudentTestResult} stores session-level metadata: user, topic, initial and final difficulty, score percentage (auto-computed), status, timestamps, and JSON fields for answers data, adaptive analysis, and difficulty progression. \texttt{QuestionPerformance} stores per-question details: question text, options, selected and correct answers, time taken, AI-predicted difficulty, recommended next difficulty, and the full CrewAI reasoning and recommendation text, with a unique constraint on (test\_result, question\_number). \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory} provides a focused record of the SOLTA pipeline output per question: current and next difficulty, correctness, time taken, and the agent's reasoning.

\subsection{Advantages of LLM-Native Adaptation}
A key design decision is the delegation of all difficulty reasoning to LLM agents rather than deterministic formulas. This offers several advantages. First, the adaptation rules can be expressed and modified entirely in natural language without rewriting scoring code, improving maintainability. Second, the agents can incorporate contextual nuance---such as recognizing borderline cases in time thresholds---that rigid numeric formulas cannot express; SOLPA interprets ``fast'' and ``slow'' contextually rather than through hard-coded second boundaries. Third, the full reasoning chain is available in the agent output, providing educators with a natural language explanation for every difficulty decision, directly supporting the explainability goals outlined in the APOT framework \cite{outay2024}. Fourth, eliminating pre-calibrated IRT parameters makes the system deployable in any domain without prior item bank construction \cite{hambleton1985}. Fifth, the LLM-driven question generation eliminates the traditional bottleneck entirely---new domains require only a topic name and difficulty level to operate, with no pilot testing or statistical calibration.

The primary trade-off is the non-determinism inherent in LLM outputs, which means identical inputs may occasionally produce slightly different outputs. This is mitigated by the structured output format enforced through task descriptions, the line-by-line keyword parsing with hard ``Medium'' defaults on failure, and critically by the synchronous rule-based fallback layer that guarantees deterministic behavior for the real-time question selection path.

