\section{Conclusion and Future Work}
% -------------------------------------------------------

This paper presented an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System that operationalizes the APOT framework \cite{outay2024} in a fully LLM-driven adaptive testing context. By mapping SOLMA (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent), SOLPA (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent), and SOLTA (Stage of Learning Transition Agent) to three CrewAI agents powered by Gemini 2.5 Flash, the system replaces deterministic scoring and IRT pre-calibration with prompt-engineered LLM reasoning over answer correctness and response time. The LSAA (Learning Style Assessment Agent) function is realized through domain-aware question generation across Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability.

The dual-layer architecture---combining a synchronous rule-based fallback for real-time responsiveness with an asynchronous multi-agent AI pipeline for rich post-assessment insights---demonstrates that production-grade adaptive testing can coexist with computationally intensive LLM pipelines. The LLM-driven dynamic question generation eliminates the traditional requirement for pre-curated, statistically validated item banks. Design-level analysis confirms complete transition-space coverage, logically consistent behavior across representative performance scenarios, and a natural language audit trail for every difficulty decision. The system demonstrates that LLM-native multi-agent architectures can implement adaptive testing logic that is simultaneously interpretable, deployable without pre-calibrated item banks, and extensible through simple prompt modification.

Future work will focus on: (1)~conducting user studies with diverse student populations to empirically validate the accuracy of LLM-predicted difficulty labels against expert annotations; (2)~extending the LSAA function with an explicit learning-style profiling agent that adapts question format based on detected learner preferences; (3)~integrating session-level memory (\texttt{memory=True} in CrewAI) to enable cross-question performance tracking and long-horizon difficulty planning by SOLTA; (4)~exploring prompt optimization techniques to reduce LLM output variability and improve structured output reliability; (5)~comparing LLM-based adaptation decisions against IRT-based ground truth on standardized item banks to quantify agreement rates; and (6)~deploying for concurrent multi-user assessment sessions with real-time difficulty dashboards for instructors, leveraging the Celery and Redis infrastructure already present in the technology stack.

